\begin{proposition}[${\operatorname{HA}} + {\operatorname{EM}}_2$]\label{proposition: Erdossubtree}
For every $k \geq 2$ and for every recursive coloring $c_a: [{\mathbb{N}}]^2 \to k$, there exists an Erd\H{o}s' tree $T$ for the coloring $c_a$ which satisfies the following properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item[{\normalfont(a)}] there exists some $\Delta^0_2$ predicate in ${\operatorname{HA}}$ which represents $x \in T$; 
\item[{\normalfont(b)}] $T$ has a unique infinite branch $r$ defined by some predicate of ${\operatorname{HA}}$;
\item[{\normalfont(c)}] if there exist infinitely many edges with color $h$ in $T$, then there are infinitely many edges with color $h$ in $r$.
\end{itemize}
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
Let $k\geq 2$. The standard Erd\H{o}s' tree $({\mathbb{N}}, \prec_E)$ associated to a coloring $c_a : [{\mathbb{N}}]^2 \to k$ is defined as a graph, as the set of natural numbers equipped with the following relation.

$({\mathbb{N}}, \prec_E)$ is recursively enumerable on the coloring, and recursive enumerable if the coloring is recursive. We would like to apply Theorem \ref{theorem:k+1} to produce an infinite branch $r$ as required, but Theorem \ref{theorem:k+1} requires a tree given as set of branches. Thus, we have to prove in ${\operatorname{HA}}$ that given a graph-tree $(N,\prec_E)$ we can extract a tree $(\tilde{E}, \prec)$ where $\tilde{E} \subset {\operatorname{List}}(k)$ which keeps all information we need. We define $(a_0, \dots, a_j) \in \tilde{E}$ if and only if there are nodes $x_0, \dots, x_{j+1} \in {\mathbb{N}}$ such that for every $i \in j+1$ $c(x_i, x_{i+1})=a_j$ and $x_{i+1}$ is a $\prec_E$-child of $x_i$. $({\mathbb{N}}, \prec_E)$ contains the value of each node while the tree $(\tilde{E}, \prec)$ contains only the color of each edge, but note that given both $({\mathbb{N}}, \prec_E)$ and $(\tilde{E}, \prec)$, we can recursively translate any subtree of $(\tilde{E}, \prec)$ in a subtree of $({\mathbb{N}}, \prec_E)$. 

By applying Theorem \ref{theorem:k+1} to the $k$-ary tree $(\tilde{E}, \prec)$, the subtree $T$ of $({\mathbb{N}}, \prec_E)$ which corresponds to $f_C''{\mathbb{N}}$ is $\Delta^0_2$ and has exactly one infinite branch, the rightmost. 
\end{proof}

Let $T$ be the witness of Proposition \ref{proposition: Erdossubtree}. We may prove that there are infinitely many nodes of the same color in the infinite branch of $T$ using only ${\operatorname{{{3}}}$. Any infinite subset of the infinite branch of $T$ with all nodes in the same color will be some monochromatic set for the original graph. Moreover our proof recursively defines $k$-many monochromatic $\Delta^0_3$-sets, one of each color, that can not be all finite, even if we can not decide which of these is the infinite one.



\begin{theorem}\label{KoenigRamsey}
Let $k \geq 2$. Then ${\operatorname{{{3}}}$ implies  ${\operatorname{RT}}^2_k(\Sigma^0_0)$ in ${\operatorname{HA}}$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}


Given $T$ the witness of Proposition \ref{proposition: Erdossubtree}, we can prove Ramsey's Theorem for pairs and $k$-many colors in ${{3}}\mbox{-}\!{\operatorname{LLPO}}$.  We have to prove that the infinite branch of $T$ (which exists and it is unique by Proposition \ref{proposition: Erdossubtree}.b) has infinitely many pairs $x \prec_T y$ of color $h$. By Proposition \ref{proposition: Erdossubtree}.c, it is enough to prove that $T$ has infinitely many pairs $x \prec_T y$ of color $c$, for some $h$. By Proposition \ref{proposition: Erdossubtree}.a, $x \in T$ is a $\Delta^0_2$ predicate. Thus, if we apply the Pigeonhole Principle for $\Sigma^0_2$ predicates $(k-1)$-many times, we deduce that $T$ has infinitely many edges in color $h$ for some $h \in k$. However, the Pigeonhole Principle for $\Sigma^0_2$ predicates is a classical principle, therefore we have to derive the particular instance we use from ${\operatorname{{{3}}}$.

\begin{claim}\label{principiocassetti}
${\operatorname{{{3}}}$ implies the Pigeonhole Principle for $\Sigma^0_2$.
\end{claim}

